I"Æ<h2 id="using-github-on-command-prompt">Using Github on command prompt.</h2>
<hr />

<p>Github is Repository storage.<br />
Repository is a remote directory that can be shared by others.<br />
You can push or pull repository files from the github storage.</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <h2 id="git-push">Git push</h2>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>To push current directoryâ€™s files onto the github repository, one has to add and commit beforehand.</p>
<ul>
  <li>Git add
Git add specifies which files to upload.
-Git commit
git commit allows the user to add comments to the push.</li>
</ul>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>Usage

git add &lt;directory-path&gt;
git commit -m "&lt;message&gt;"
git push

Example

gid add .
gid commit -m "Hello World"
git push

</code></pre></div></div>

<ul>
  <li>
    <h2 id="git-clone">Git clone</h2>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>To clone the github repository to a local directory, one has to clone the repositoryâ€™s https address.</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>Usage

git clone &lt;https-address&gt;

Example

git clone https://github.com/btjklee/blog.git
</code></pre></div></div>

<ul>
  <li>
    <h2 id="git-pull">Git pull</h2>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>Unlike Git Push, in which the github repository is updated FROM my directoryâ€™s changes, Git Pull updates my local directory using the repositoryâ€™s changes.</p>

<p>However, git pull is useful when multiple people are updating one repository, so I will not write down how to use it just yet.</p>

<hr />

<h3 id="if-i-want-to-make-a-new-repository">If I want to make a new repository?</h3>

<ol>
  <li>Go to github.com and create new repository</li>
  <li>Get the https address from the new repository</li>
  <li>Go to CMD and git clone the https address to the desired local directory</li>
  <li>Once the local directory and the github repository are connected, start coding.</li>
  <li>After changes have been made, go to the command prompt,
    <div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>git add.
git commit -m "example"
git push
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
</ol>

